# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-limiter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In the frequency domain, clipping produces strong harmonics in the high-frequency range (as the clipped waveform comes closer to a square wave).
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The extra high-frequency weighting of the signal could make tweeter damage more likely than if the signal were not clipped.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In most cases, the distortion associated with clipping is unwanted, and is visible on an oscilloscope even if it is inaudible.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] However, clipping is often used in music for artistic effect, particularly guitar-dominant genres like blues, rock, and metal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] When an amplifier is pushed to create a signal with more power than its power supply can produce, it will amplify the signal only up to its maximum capacity, at which point the signal can be amplified no further.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] As the signal simply "cuts" or "clips" at the maximum capacity of the amplifier, the signal is said to be "clipping".
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The extra signal, which is beyond the capability of the amplifier, is simply cut off, resulting in a sine wave becoming a distorted square-wave-type waveform.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Amplifiers have voltage, current and thermal limits.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Clipping may occur due to limitations in the power supply or the output stage.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Some amplifiers are able to deliver peak power without clipping for short durations before energy stored in the power supply is depleted or the amplifier begins to overheat.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Many electric guitar players intentionally *overdrive* their amplifiers (or insert a fuzz box) to cause clipping in order to get a desired sound .
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Because the clipped waveform has more area underneath it than the smaller unclipped waveform, the amplifier produces more power than its rated (sine wave) output when it is clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] This extra power can damage the loudspeaker.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] It may cause damage to the amplifier's power supply or simply blow a fuse.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The additional high-frequency energy in the harmonics generated by an amplifier operating in clipping can damage the tweeter in a connected loudspeaker via overheating.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Clipping can occur within a system as processing (e.g., an all-pass filter) can change the phase relationship between spectral components of a signal in such a way as to create excessive peak outputs.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The excessive peaks may become clipped even though the system can play any simple sine wave signals of the same level without clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Electric guitarists frequently and intentionally overdrive their guitar amplifiers to cause clipping and other distortion in order to get a desired sound.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In digital signal processing, clipping occurs when the signal is restricted by the range of a chosen representation.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] For example, in a system using 16-bit signed integers, 32767 is the largest positive value that can be represented.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] If, during processing, the amplitude of the signal is doubled, sample values of, for instance, 32000 should become 64000, but instead cause an integer overflow and saturate to the maximum, 32767.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Clipping is preferable to the alternative in digital systems—wrapping—which occurs if the digital processor is allowed to overflow, ignoring the most significant bits of the magnitude, and sometimes even the sign of the sample value, resulting in gross distortion of the signal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The simplest way to avoid clipping is to reduce the signal level.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Alternatively, the system can be improved to support a higher signal level without clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Some audiophiles will use amplifiers that are rated for power outputs over twice the speaker's ratings.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Since clipping can be thought of as acting as a crude form of signal limiter, a proper limiter can be used to safely and dynamically bring the levels of the loud parts of a signal down (for example, bass and snare drums).
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Many amplifier designers have incorporated circuits to prevent clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The simplest circuits act like a fast limiter, which engages about one decibel before the clipping point.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] A more complex circuit, called "soft-clip", has been used from the 1980s onward to limit the signal at the input stage.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The soft-clip feature begins to engage prior to clipping, for instance, starting at 10 dB below maximum output power.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The output waveform retains a rounded characteristic even in the presence of an overload input signal as much as 10 dB higher than maximum specified.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] It is preferable to avoid clipping, but if a recording has clipped and cannot be re-recorded, repair is an option.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The goal of repair is to make up a plausible replacement for the clipped part of the signal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Complex hard-clipped signals cannot be restored to their original state because the information contained in the peaks that are clipped is completely lost.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Soft-clipped signals can be restored to their original state to within a case-dependent tolerance because no part of the original signal is completely lost.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In this case, the degree of information loss is proportional to the degree of compression caused by the clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Lightly clipped bandwidth-limited signals that are highly oversampled have the potential for perfect repair.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Several methods can partially restore a clipped signal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Once the clipped portion is known, one can attempt partial recovery.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] One such method is interpolation or extrapolation of known samples.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Advanced implementations may use cubic splines to attempt to restore a continuously differentiable signal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] While these reconstructions are only an approximation of the original, the subjective quality may be improved.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Other methods include copying the signal directly from one stereo channel to another, as it may be the case that only one channel is clipped.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Several software solutions of varying results and methods exist to repair clipping: CrumplePop ClipRemover, MAGIX Sound Forge, iZotope RX De-Clip, Acon Digital Restoration Suite, Adobe Audition, Thimeo Stereo Tool, declipping solutions from CEDAR Audio, and Audacity plugins such as Clip Fix.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] An amplifier may have an asymmetrical output swing and clipping may begin earlier on one half of the output waveform.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In audio amplifiers using unregulated linear power supplies, if the filter capacitor is not large enough, it is possible for ripple voltage to cause clipping that also contains some AC line frequency harmonics.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In a switched-mode power supply the switching frequency is more dominant in the ripple voltage and outside the audio band, while in a regulated power supply the ripple voltage is rejected.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] A vacuum tube can only move a limited number of electrons in a given amount of time, dependent on its size, temperature, and metals.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The resulting fall-off in amplification with increasing output current results in *soft clipping*.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Amplifying devices may also have limits on their inputs, for example, excessive base current to a bipolar transistor or excessive grid current to a vacuum tube.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Operating outside these limits can distort the input signal, if it comes from a high enough impedance source, or damage the amplifying device, requiring a limiting circuit for protection; see below.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] An amplifier may limit its current output, or the input voltage, for a variety of reasons, both intentional or not.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Intentional limiting circuits would not be expected to come into effect in normal operation, but only when the output load resistance is too low or the input signal level is exceptionally high, for example.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The result of this form of clipping might not create a flat top to the voltage waveform, but rather a flat top to the current waveform.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] A transformer (most commonly used between stages and at the output in tube equipment) will clip when its ferromagnetic core becomes electromagnetically saturated.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Clipping in a circuit can be detected by comparing the original input signal with an output signal with adjustment for applied gain.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] For instance, if a circuit has 10 dB of applied gain, it can be tested for clipping by attenuating the output signal by 10 dB and comparing it to the input signal.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] The difference between the two signals can be used to illuminate clipping detection indicators and can be used to decrease the gain of a preceding circuit to manage clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] Clipped signals will often be squarized, where third harmonics are contextual outliers in a Fourier Transform.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] In the case of an expected sine wave, the presence of odd harmonics will often suggest the signal has been hard clipped.
[src:audio-limiter/clipping-audio] A “soft clip” will have a knee on both sides of the plateau, which will show the presence of several even overtones in the lower frequency spectrum.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A dedicated electronic hardware unit or audio software that applies compression is called a **compressor**.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In the 2000s, compressors became available as software plugins that run in digital audio workstation software.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In recorded and live music, compression parameters may be adjusted to change the way they affect sounds.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression and limiting are identical in process but different in degree and perceived effect.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A limiter is a compressor with a high ratio and, generally, a short attack time.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used to improve performance and clarity in public address systems, as an effect and to improve consistency in mixing and mastering.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] It is used on voice to reduce sibilance and in broadcasting and advertising specifically to make an audio program stand out.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] It is an integral technology in some noise reduction systems.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] There are two types of compression: downward and upward.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Both types of compression reduce the dynamic range of an audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors also have the ability to do the *opposite* of compression, namely *expansion*.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Expansion *increases* the dynamic range of the audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Like compression, expansion comes in two types, downward and upward.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The signal entering a compressor is split; one copy is sent to a variable-gain amplifier and the other to a *side-chain* where the signal level is measured and a circuit controlled by the measured signal level applies the required gain to the amplifier.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This design, known as a *feed-forward* type, is used today in most compressors.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Earlier designs were based on a *feedback* layout where the signal level was measured after the amplifier.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] There are a number of technologies used for variable-gain amplification, each having different advantages and disadvantages.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Vacuum tubes are used in a configuration called *variable-mu* where the grid-to-cathode voltage changes to alter the gain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Optical compressors use a photoresistor stimulated by a small lamp (incandescent, LED, or electroluminescent panel) to create changes in signal gain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Other technologies used include field effect transistors and a diode bridge.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] When working with digital audio, digital signal processing (DSP) techniques are commonly used to implement compression as audio plug-ins, in mixing consoles, and in digital audio workstations.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Often the algorithms are used to emulate the above analog technologies.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A number of user-adjustable control parameters and features are used to adjust dynamic range compression signal processing algorithms and components.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor reduces the level of an audio signal if its amplitude exceeds a certain *threshold*.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Threshold is commonly set in decibels (dBFS for digital compressors and dBu for hardware compressors), where a lower threshold (e.g. −60 dB) means a larger portion of the signal is treated.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] When the signal level is below the threshold, no processing is performed and the input signal is passed, unmodified, to the output.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Thus a higher threshold of, e.g., −5 dB, results in less processing, less compression.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Threshold timing behavior is subject to attack and release settings (see below).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] When the signal level goes above threshold, compressor operation is delayed by the *attack* setting.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] For an amount of time determined by the *release* after the input signal has fallen below the threshold, the compressor continues to apply dynamic range compression.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The amount of gain reduction is determined by **ratio**: a ratio of 4:1 means that if input level is 4 dB over the threshold, the output signal level is reduced to 1 dB over the threshold.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The gain and output level has been reduced by 3 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Another way of stating this is that any input signal level over the threshold will, in this case, be output at a level which is only 25% (i.e.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] 1 over 4) as much over the threshold as its input level was.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The highest ratio of $\infty$ :1 is often known as *limiting*, and effectively denotes that any signal above the threshold is brought down to the threshold level once the *attack* time has expired.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor may provide a degree of control over how quickly it acts.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The *attack* is the period when the compressor is decreasing gain in response to the increased level at the input to reach the gain determined by the ratio.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The *release* is the period when the compressor is increasing gain in response to reduced level at the input to reach the output gain determined by the ratio, or, to unity, once the input level has fallen below the threshold.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Because the loudness pattern of the source material is modified by the time-varying operation of compressor, it may change the character of the signal in subtle to quite noticeable ways depending on the attack and release settings used.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The length of each period is determined by the rate of change and the required change in gain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] For more intuitive operation, a compressor's attack and release controls are labeled as a unit of time (often milliseconds).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is the amount of time it takes for the gain to change a set amount of dB or a set percentage towards the target gain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] There is no industry standard for the exact meaning of these time parameters.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In many compressors, the attack and release times are adjustable by the user.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors, however, have the attack and release times determined by the circuit design and cannot be adjusted.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Sometimes the attack and release times are *automatic* or *program dependent*, meaning that the behavior may change depending on the input signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Another control a compressor might offer is knee selection.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This controls whether the bend in the response curve between below threshold and above threshold is abrupt (hard) or gradual (soft).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A soft knee slowly increases the compression ratio as the level increases and eventually reaches the compression ratio set by the user.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A soft knee reduces the potentially audible transition from uncompressed to compressed, and is especially applicable for higher ratio settings where the changeover at the threshold would be more noticeable.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A peak-sensing compressor responds to the peak level of the input signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] While providing tighter peak level control, peak level sensing does not necessarily relate to human perception of loudness.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Some compressors apply a power measurement function (commonly root mean square or RMS) on the input signal before comparing its level to the threshold.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This produces a more relaxed compression that more closely relates to human perception of loudness.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor in *stereo linking* mode applies the same amount of gain reduction to both the left and right channels.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is done to prevent image shifting that can occur if each channel is compressed individually.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Because a downward compressor only reduces the level of the signal, the ability to add a fixed amount of *make-up gain* at the output is usually provided so that an optimum output level is produced.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The look-ahead function is designed to overcome the problem of being forced to compromise between slow attack rates that produce smooth-sounding gain changes, and fast attack rates capable of catching transients.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Look-ahead is implemented by splitting the input signal and delaying one side (the audio signal) by the look-ahead time.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The non-delayed side (the gain control signal) is used to drive the compression of the delayed signal, which then appears at the output.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This way a smooth-sounding slower attack rate can be used to catch transients.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The cost of this solution is added audio latency through the processor.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is often applied in audio systems for restaurants, retail, and similar public environments that play background music at a relatively low volume and need it compressed, not just to keep the volume fairly constant, but also to make quiet parts of the music audible over ambient noise.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression can increase average output gain of a power amplifier by 50 to 100% with a reduced dynamic range.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] For paging and evacuation systems, this adds clarity under noisy circumstances and saves on the number of amplifiers required.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is often used in music production to make instruments more consistent in dynamic range, so that they "sit" more nicely in the mix with the other instruments (neither disappear during short periods of time, nor overpower the other instruments during short periods).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Vocal performances in rock music or pop music are compressed for the same reason.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression can also be used on instrument sounds to create effects not primarily focused on stabilizing the volume.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] For instance, drum and cymbal sounds tend to decay quickly, but a compressor can make the sound appear to have a more sustained tail.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Guitar sounds are often compressed to produce a fuller, more sustained sound.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Adjusting the attack and release time of a compressor can be used increase contrast between the transient and sustain parts of a sounds envelope.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Most devices capable of compressing audio dynamics can also be used to reduce the volume of one audio source when another audio source reaches a certain level; this is called side-chaining.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In electronic dance music, side-chaining is often used on basslines, controlled by the kick drum or a similar percussive trigger, to prevent the two from conflicting, and provide a pulsating, rhythmic dynamic to the sound.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor can be used to reduce sibilance ('ess' sounds) in vocals (de-essing) by feeding the compressor's side-chain an equalized version of the input signal, so that specific, sibilance-related frequencies (typically 4000 to 8000 hz) activate the compressor more.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used in voice communications in amateur radio that employ single-sideband (SSB) modulation to make a particular station's signal more readable to a distant station, or to make one's station's transmitted signal stand out against others.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] An SSB signal's strength depends on the level of modulation.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor increases the average level of the modulation signal thus increasing the transmitted signal strength.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Most modern amateur radio SSB transceivers have speech compressors built-in.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is also used in land mobile radio, especially in transmitted audio of professional walkie-talkies and remote control dispatch consoles.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression is used extensively in broadcasting to boost the perceived volume of sound while reducing the dynamic range of source audio.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] To avoid overmodulation, broadcasters in most countries have legal limits on instantaneous peak volume they may broadcast.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Normally these limits are met by permanently inserted compression hardware in the on-air chain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Broadcasters use compressors in order that their station sounds louder than comparable stations.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The effect is to make the more heavily compressed station jump out at the listener at a given volume setting.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is not limited to inter-channel differences; they also exist between programme material within the same channel.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Loudness differences are a frequent source of audience complaints, especially TV commercials and promos that seem too loud.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) has been addressing this issue in the EBU PLOUD group, which consists of over 240 audio professionals, many from broadcasters and equipment manufacturers.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In 2010, the EBU published EBU R 128 which introduces a new way of metering and normalizing audio.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The Recommendation uses ITU-R BS.1770 loudness metering.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] As of 2016, several European TV stations have announced their support for the new norm and over 20 manufacturers have announced products supporting the new *EBU Mode* loudness meters.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] To help audio engineers understand what loudness range their material consists of (e.g. to check if some compression may be needed to fit it into the channel of a specific delivery platform), the EBU also introduced the *Loudness Range* (LRA) descriptor.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Most television commercials are heavily compressed to achieve near-maximum perceived loudness while staying within permissible limits.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This causes a problem that TV viewers often notice: when a station switches from minimally compressed program material to a heavily compressed commercial, the volume sometimes seems to increase dramatically.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Peak loudness might be the same—meeting the letter of the law—but high compression puts much more of the audio in the commercial at close to the maximum allowable, making the commercial seem much louder.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Record companies, mixing engineers and mastering engineers have been gradually increasing the overall loudness of commercial albums.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is achieved by using higher degrees of compression and limiting during mixing and mastering; compression algorithms have been engineered specifically to accomplish the task of maximizing audio level in the digital stream.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Hard limiting or clipping can result, affecting the tone and timbre of the music.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The effort to increase loudness has been referred to as the loudness war.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Noise reduction systems use a compressor to reduce the dynamic range of a signal for transmission or recording, expanding it afterward, a process called companding.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This reduces the effects of a channel or recording medium with limited dynamic range.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Instrument amplifiers often include compression circuitry to prevent sudden high-wattage peaks that could damage the speakers.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Electric bass players often use compression effects, either effects units available in pedal, rackmount units, or built-in devices in bass amps, to even out the sound levels of their basslines.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Gain pumping, where a regular amplitude peak (such as a kick drum) causes the rest of the mix to change in volume due to the compressor, is generally avoided in music production.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] However, many dance and hip-hop musicians purposefully use this phenomenon, causing the mix to alter in volume rhythmically in time with the beat.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Hearing aids use a compressor to bring the audio volume into the listener's hearing range.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] To help the patient perceive the direction sound comes from, some hearing aids use binaural compression.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compressors are also used for hearing protection in some electronic active hearing protection earmuffs and earplugs, to let sounds at ordinary volumes be heard normally while attenuating louder sounds, possibly also amplifying softer sounds.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This allows, for example, shooters wearing hearing protection at a shooting range to converse normally, while sharply attenuating the much louder sounds of the gunshots, and similarly for musicians to hear quiet music but be protected from loud noises such as drums or cymbal crashes.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In applications of machine learning where an algorithm is training on audio samples, dynamic range compression is a way to augment samples for a larger data set.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A limiter is a compressor with a high ratio and, generally, a fast attack time.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Compression with ratio of 10:1 or more is generally considered limiting.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Some bass amps and PA system amplifiers include limiters to prevent sudden volume peaks from causing distortion or damaging the speakers.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A compressor with a side-chain input controls gain from main input to output based on the level of the signal at the side-chain input.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] An early innovator of side-chain compression in an effects unit was the Eventide Omnipressor from 1974.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] With side-chaining, the compressor behaves in the conventional manner when both main and side-chain inputs are supplied with the same signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The side-chain input is used by disc jockeys for ducking – lowering the music volume automatically when speaking.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The DJ's microphone signal is routed to the side-chain input so that whenever the DJ speaks the compressor reduces the volume of the music.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] A sidechain with equalization controls can be used to reduce the volume of signals that have a strong spectral content within a certain frequency range: it can act as a de-esser, reducing the level of vocal sibilance in the range of 6–9 kHz.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Another use of the side-chain in music production serves to maintain a loud bass track without the bass drum causing undue peaks that result in loss of overall headroom.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Inserting the compressor in a parallel signal path is known as parallel compression.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] It is a form of upward compression that facilitates dynamic control without significant audible side effects so long as the ratio is relatively low and the compressor's sound is relatively neutral.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] On the other hand, a high compression ratio with significant audible artifacts can be chosen in one of the two parallel signal paths.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is used by some concert mixers and recording engineers as an artistic effect called *New York compression* or *Motown compression*.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Combining a linear signal with a compressor and then reducing the output gain of the compression chain results in low-level detail enhancement without any peak reduction; The compressor significantly adds to the combined gain at low levels only.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Multiband compressors can act differently on different frequency bands.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The advantage of multiband compression over full-bandwidth compression is that problems related to a specific frequency range can be fixed without unnecessary compression in the other, unrelated frequencies.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The downside is that frequency-specific compression is more complex and requires more processing capacity than full-bandwidth compression and can introduce phase issues.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Multiband compressors work by first splitting the signal through some number of band-pass filters, crossover filters or filter banks.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Each split signal then passes through its own compressor and is independently adjustable for threshold, ratio, attack, and release.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The signals are then recombined and an additional limiting circuit may be employed to ensure that the combined signals do not create unwanted peak levels.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In music production, multiband compressors are primarily an audio mastering tool, but their inclusion in digital audio workstation plug-in sets is increasing their use among mix engineers.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The TC Electronic Finalizer included a three band compressor and was a popular audio mastering tool around year 2000.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] On-air signal chains of radio stations commonly use multiband compressors to increase loudness while avoiding overmodulation.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Having a louder sound is often considered an advantage in commercial broadcasting.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In recent years, aggressive multiband compression (known as OTT, after a preset for Ableton Lives stock multiband compressor) , has become associated with a certain sonic character often pursued loud electronic music genres like Dubstep.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Serial compression is a technique used in sound recording and mixing.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Serial compression is achieved by using two fairly different compressors in a signal chain.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] One compressor generally stabilizes the dynamic range while the other aggressively compresses stronger peaks.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This is the normal internal signal routing in common combination devices marketed as *compressor-limiters*, where an RMS compressor (for general gain control) is followed by a fast peak-sensing limiter (for overload protection).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Done properly, even heavy serial compression can sound natural in a way not possible with a single compressor.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] It is most often used to even out erratic vocals and guitars.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Some software audio players support plugins that implement compression.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] These can increase loudness of audio tracks, or level out the volume of highly-variable music (such as classical music, or a playlist that spans multiple music types).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] This improves the listenability of audio played through poor-quality speakers, or when played in noisy environments (such as in a car or during a party).
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In an article published in January 2014 by the *Journal of the Audio Engineering Society*, Emmanuel Deruty and Damien Tardieu performed a systematic study describing the influence of compressors and brickwall limiters on the musical audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The experiment involved four software limiters: Waves L2, Sonnox Oxford Limiter, Thomas Mundt's Loudmax, Blue Cat's Protector, as well as four software compressors: Waves H-Comp, Sonnox Oxford Dynamics, Sonalksis SV-3157, and URS 1970.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The study provides objective data on what limiters and compressors do to the audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Five signal descriptors were considered: RMS power, EBU R 128 integrated loudness, crest factor, R 128 LRA, and density of clipped samples.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] RMS power accounts for the signal's physical level, R 128 loudness for the perceived level.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] The crest factor, which is the difference between the signal's peak and its average power, is on occasions considered as a basis for the measure of micro-dynamics, for instance in the *TT Dynamic Range Meter* plug-in.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Finally, R 128 LRA has been repeatedly considered as a measure of macro-dynamics or dynamics in the musical sense.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, limiters increase both physical and perceptual levels, increase the density of clipped samples, decrease the crest factor and decrease macro-dynamics (LRA) given that the amount of limiting is substantial.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] As far as the compressors are concerned, the authors performed two processing sessions, using a fast attack (0.5 ms) in one case, and a slow attack (50 ms) in the other.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] Make-up gain is deactivated, but the resulting file is normalized.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, fast-attack compressors increase both physical and perceptual levels, but only slightly.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] They decrease the density of clipped samples, and decrease both crest factor and macro-dynamics.
[src:audio-limiter/dynamic-range-compression] In other words, slow-attack compressors decrease both physical and perceptual levels, decrease macro-dynamics, but have no influence on crest factor and clipped sample density.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] In electronics, **gain** is a measure of the ability of a two-port circuit (often an amplifier) to increase the power or amplitude of a signal from the input to the output port by adding energy converted from some power supply to the signal.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] It is usually defined as the mean ratio of the signal amplitude or power at the output port to the amplitude or power at the input port.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] It is often expressed using the logarithmic decibel (dB) units ("dB gain").
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] A gain greater than one (greater than zero dB), that is, amplification, is the defining property of an active device or circuit, while a passive circuit will have a gain of less than one.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The term *gain* alone is ambiguous, and can refer to the ratio of output to input voltage (*voltage gain*), current (*current gain*) or electric power (*power gain*).
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] In the field of audio and general purpose amplifiers, especially operational amplifiers, the term usually refers to voltage gain, but in radio frequency amplifiers it usually refers to power gain.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] Furthermore, the term gain is also applied in systems such as sensors where the input and output have different units; in such cases the gain units must be specified, as in "5 microvolts per photon" for the responsivity of a photosensor.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The "gain" of a bipolar transistor normally refers to forward current transfer ratio, either *h*FE ("beta", the static ratio of *I**c* divided by *I*b at some operating point), or sometimes *h*fe (the small-signal current gain, the slope of the graph of *I**c* against *I**b* at a point).
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The gain of an electronic device or circuit generally varies with the frequency of the applied signal.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] Unless otherwise stated, the term refers to the gain for frequencies in the passband, the intended operating frequency range of the equipment.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The term *gain* has a different meaning in antenna design; antenna gain is the ratio of radiation intensity from a directional antenna to $P_{\text{in}}/4\pi$ (mean radiation intensity from a lossless antenna).
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] where $P_{\text{in}}$ is the power applied to the input, $P_{\text{out}}$ is the power from the output.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] This simplified formula, the 20 log rule, is used to calculate a **voltage gain** in decibels and is equivalent to a power gain if and only if the impedances at input and output are equal.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] This simplified formula is used to calculate a **current gain** in decibels and is equivalent to the power gain if and only if the impedances at input and output are equal.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The "current gain" of a bipolar transistor, $h_{\text{FE}}$ or $h_{\text{fe}}$ , is normally given as a dimensionless number, the ratio of $I_{\text{c}}$ to $I_{\text{b}}$ (or slope of the $I_{\text{c}}$ -versus- $I_{\text{b}}$ graph, for $h_{\text{fe}}$ ).
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] In the cases above, gain will be a dimensionless quantity, as it is the ratio of like units (decibels are not used as units, but rather as a method of indicating a logarithmic relationship).
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] In the bipolar transistor example, it is the ratio of the output current to the input current, both measured in amperes.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] In the case of other devices, the gain will have a value in SI units.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] Such is the case with the operational transconductance amplifier, which has an open-loop gain (transconductance) in siemens (mhos), because the gain is a ratio of the output current to the input voltage.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] An amplifier has an input impedance of 50 ohms and drives a load of 50 ohms.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] When its input ( $V_{\text{in}}$ ) is 1 volt, its output ( $V_{\text{out}}$ ) is 10 volts.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] The units V/V are optional but make it clear that this figure is a voltage gain and not a power gain.
[src:audio-limiter/gain-electronics] A gain of factor 1 (equivalent to 0 dB) where both input and output are at the same voltage level and impedance is also known as *unity gain*.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] In electronics, a **limiter** is a circuit that allows signals below a specified input power or level to pass unaffected while attenuating (lowering) the peaks of stronger signals that exceed this threshold.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Limiting is a type of dynamic range compression.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Clipping is an extreme version of limiting.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Limiters are common as a safety device in broadcast applications to prevent overmodulation and in audio mastering to avoid digital clipping, lossy coding errors, or the phonograph needle from jumping out of the groove.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Limiters are also used as protective features in some components of sound reinforcement systems (e.g., powered mixing boards and power amplifiers) and in some bass amplifiers, to prevent unwanted distortion or loudspeaker damage.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Limiting can refer to a range of treatments designed to limit the maximum level of a signal.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] For military two-way radio sets and aircraft VHF voice telecommunications, the voice limiter is known as a vogad.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] It is designed to work with high levels of background noise near the microphone.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] One form operates by up-converting the audio signal to an ultrasonic frequency, hard limiting that signal, and then down converting the result.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] The frequency conversion uses image-cancelling heterodyning.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] The advantage of clipping the supersonic signal is that the odd harmonics produced will still be out-of-band when down converted.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] This is in contrast to standard hard limiting, as in an electric guitar fuzz box, where the harmonics are highly audible.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] This device ultimately gives a distinctive character to the voice communication, which, despite being highly distorted, ensures spoken words remain clear.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Bass instrument amplifiers and power amplifiers are more commonly equipped with limiter circuitry to prevent overloading the power amplifier and to protect speakers.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Electric guitar amps do not usually have limiters.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] PIN diodes can be used in limiter circuits to reflect the energy back to the source or clip the signal.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Mastering engineers often use limiting combined with make-up gain to increase the perceived loudness of an audio recording during the audio mastering process.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] An FM radio receiver usually has at least one stage of amplification that performs a limiting function.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] This stage provides a constant level of signal to the FM demodulator stage, reducing the effect of input signal level changes to the output.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] If two or more signals are received at the same time, a high-performance limiter stage can greatly reduce the effect of the weaker signals on the output.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] This is commonly referred to as the FM capture effect.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Generally, FM demodulators are not affected by amplitude variations, since the baseband is contained in the frequency deviations.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] Some detectors, including the ratio detector, inherently limit gain by the nature of the circuit design.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] In AM radio, the information is located in the amplitude variations, and distortion can occur due to spurious signals that could cause the baseband to be misrepresented.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] In Canada, while the cold weather rule is in effect, limiters are used to lower the capacity of houses of non-paying customers.
[src:audio-limiter/limiter] The limiters allow enough power to run a furnace and a few lights.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] In acoustics, **loudness** is the subjective perception of sound pressure.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] More formally, it is defined as the "attribute of auditory sensation in terms of which sounds can be ordered on a scale extending from quiet to loud".
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The relation of physical attributes of sound to perceived loudness includes physical, physiological and psychological components.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The study of **apparent loudness** is included in the topic of psychoacoustics and employs methods of psychophysics.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] In different industries, loudness may have different meanings and different measurement standards.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Some definitions, such as ITU-R BS.1770 refer to the relative loudness of different segments of electronically reproduced sounds, such as for broadcasting and cinema.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Others, such as ISO 532A (Stevens loudness, measured in sones), ISO 532B (Zwicker loudness), DIN 45631 and ASA/ANSI S3.4, have a more general scope and are often used to characterize the loudness of environmental noise.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] More modern standards, such as Nordtest ACOU112 and ISO/AWI 532-3 (in progress), take into account other components of loudness, such as onset rate, time variation and spectral masking.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness, a subjective measure, is often confused with physical measures of sound strength such as sound pressure, sound pressure level (in decibels), sound intensity or sound power.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Weighting filters such as A-weighting and LKFS attempt to compensate measurements to correspond to loudness as perceived by the typical human.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The perception of loudness is related to sound pressure level (SPL), frequency content and duration of a sound.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The relationship between SPL and loudness of a single tone can be approximated by Stevens's power law in which SPL has an exponent of 0.67.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] A more precise model known as the *Inflected Exponential function*, indicates that loudness increases with a higher exponent at low and high levels and with a lower exponent at moderate levels.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The sensitivity of the human ear changes as a function of frequency, as shown in the equal-loudness graph.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Each line on this graph shows the SPL required for frequencies to be perceived as equally loud, and different curves pertain to different sound pressure levels.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] It also shows that humans with normal hearing are most sensitive to sounds around 2–4 kHz, with sensitivity declining to either side of this region.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] A complete model of the perception of loudness will include the integration of SPL by frequency.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Historically, loudness was measured using an ear-balancing method with an audiometer in which the amplitude of a sine wave was adjusted by the user to equal the perceived loudness of the sound being evaluated.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Contemporary standards for measurement of loudness are based on the summation of energy in critical bands.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] When sensorineural hearing loss (damage to the cochlea or in the brain) is present, the perception of loudness is altered.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Sounds at low levels (often perceived by those without hearing loss as relatively quiet) are no longer audible to the hearing impaired, but sounds at high levels often are perceived as having the same loudness as they would for an unimpaired listener.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] This phenomenon can be explained by two theories, called *loudness recruitment* and *softness imperception*.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness recruitment posits that loudness grows more rapidly for certain listeners than for normal listeners with changes in level.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] This theory has been accepted as the classical explanation.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Softness imperception, a term coined by Mary Florentine around 2002, proposes that some listeners with sensorineural hearing loss may exhibit a normal rate of loudness growth, but instead have an elevated loudness at their threshold.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] That is, the softest sound that is audible to these listeners is louder than the softest sound audible to normal listeners.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The *loudness* control associated with a loudness compensation feature on some consumer stereos alters the frequency response curve to correspond roughly with the equal loudness characteristic of the ear.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness compensation is intended to make the recorded music sound more natural when played at a lower levels by boosting low frequencies, to which the ear is less sensitive at lower sound pressure levels.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness normalization is a specific type of audio normalization that equalizes perceived level such that, for instance, commercials do not sound louder than television programs.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness normalization schemes exist for a number of audio applications.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Historically sone (loudness *N*) and phon (loudness level *LN*) units have been used to measure loudness.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] A-weighting follows human sensitivity to sound and describes relative perceived loudness for at quiet to moderate speech levels, around 40 phons.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Relative loudness monitoring in production is measured in accordance with ITU-R BS.1770 in units of LKFS.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Work began on ITU-R BS.1770 in 2001 after 0 dBFS+ level distortion in converters and lossy codecs had become evident; and the original Leq(RLB) loudness metric was proposed by Gilbert Soulodre in 2003.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Based on data from subjective listening tests, Leq(RLB) compared favorably to numerous other algorithms.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] CBC, Dolby and TC Electronic and numerous broadcasters contributed to the listening tests.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] Loudness levels measured according to the Leq(RLB) specified in ITU-R BS.1770 are reported in LKFS units.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The ITU-R BS.1770 measurement system was improved for multi-channel applications (monaural to 5.1 surround sound).
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] To improve consistency across program material genres, a relative measurement gate was added.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] This work was carried out in 2008 by the EBU.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] The improvements were brought back into BS.1770-2.
[src:audio-limiter/loudness] ITU subsequently updated the true-peak metric (BS.1770-3) and added provision for even more audio channels, for instance 22.2 surround sound (BS.1770-4).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A **peak programme meter** (**PPM**) is an instrument used in professional audio that indicates the level of an audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In professional use, which requires consistent level measurements across an industry, audio level meters often comply with a formal standard.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This ensures that all compliant meters indicate the same level for a given audio signal.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The principal standard for PPMs is IEC 60268-10.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It describes two different quasi-PPM designs that have roots in meters originally developed in the 1930s for the AM radio broadcasting networks of Germany (Type I) and the United Kingdom (Type II).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The term Peak Programme Meter usually refers to these IEC-specified types and similar designs.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Though originally designed for monitoring analogue audio signals, these PPMs are now also used with digital audio.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] PPMs do not provide effective loudness monitoring.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Newer types of meters do, and there is now a push within the broadcasting industry to move away from the traditional level meters described in this article to two new types: loudness meters based on EBU Tech.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The former would be used to standardise broadcast loudness to −23 LUFS and the latter to prevent digital clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In common with many other types of audio level meter, PPMs originally used electro-mechanical displays.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] These took the form of moving-coil panel meters or mirror galvanometers with demanding 'ballistics': the key requirement being that the indicated level should rise as quickly as possible with negligible overshoot.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] These displays require active driver electronics.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Nowadays, PPMs are often implemented as 'bargraph' incremental displays using solid-state illuminated segments in a vertical or horizontal array.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] For these, IEC 60268-10 requires a minimum of 100 segments and a resolution better than 0.5 dB at the higher levels.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Many operators prefer the moving-coil meter type of display, in which a needle moves in an arc, because they feel the angular movement is easier for the human eye to monitor than the linear movement of a bar graph.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] PPMs can also be implemented in software, in a general-purpose computer or by a dedicated device that inserts a PPM image into a picture signal for display on a picture monitor.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A variety of terms, such as *line-up level* and *operating level* exist, and their meaning may vary from place to place.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In an attempt bring clarity to level definitions in the context of programme transmission from one country to another, where different technical practices may apply, ITU-R Rec.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] BS.645 defined three reference levels: Measurement Level (ML), Alignment Level (AL) and Permitted Maximum Level (PML).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This document shows the reading corresponding to these levels for several types of meters.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Alignment Level is the level of a steady sine-wave alignment tone.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Permitted Maximum Level refers to the permitted maximum *meter indication* that operators should aim for on speech, music, etc., not tone.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] PPMs often use white-on-black displays to minimise eyestrain, especially with extended periods of use.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Whichever scheme is used, usually there is a scale mark corresponding to Alignment Level.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Most PPMs have an approximately logarithmic scale, i.e., roughly linear in decibels, to provide useful indications over a wide dynamic range.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Quasi-PPMs use a short integration time so they can register peaks longer than a few milliseconds in duration.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In the original context of AM radio broadcasting in the 1930s, overloads due to shorter peaks were considered unimportant on the grounds that the human ear could not detect distortion due to momentary clipping.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Ignoring momentary clipping made it possible to increase average modulation levels.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In modern digital audio practice, where quality standards are hopefully much higher than AM radio in the 1930s, clipping of even short peaks is usually regarded as something to avoid.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] On typical, real-world audio signals, a quasi-PPM under-reads the true peak by 6 to 8 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Nevertheless, quasi-PPMs are still widely used in the digital age because of their usefulness in achieving programme balance.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Overloads are avoided by allowing, typically, 9 dB of headroom when controlling digital levels with a quasi-PPM.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The extent to which quasi-PPMs show less than the true amplitude of momentary peaks is determined by the 'integration time'.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The longer the integration time, the greater the difference between the true and indicated peaks.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In earlier standards, different methods of measurement and criteria were used, such as 0.2 Neper or 80% voltage instead of 2 dB, but the practical difference between them was small.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A Type I PPM has an integration time of 5 milliseconds and a Type II PPM has an integration time of 10 milliseconds.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] All PPMs have a return time much longer than the integration time, to give the operator more time to see the peaks and reduce eye strain.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Type I PPMs fall back 20 dB in 1.7 seconds.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Type II PPMs fall back 24 dB in 2.8 seconds.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The PPM was originally developed independently in both Germany and the United Kingdom, for use in AM radio broadcasting networks in the 1930s.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] These were quasi-peak meters with some features in common but otherwise substantially different.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] They are superior to earlier types of meters that were not good for monitoring peak audio levels.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In about 1936 and 1937, German broadcasters developed a peak programme meter with a mirror galvanometer known as a "Lichtzeigerinstrument" (light pointer) for the display.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The system consisted of a drive amplifier (e.g., ARD types U21 and U71) and a separate display unit (e.g., ARD types J47 and J48).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A stereo version, known as a "Doppel-Lichtzeigerinstrument" contained two mirror galvanometer displays in a single housing.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Such displays were still used until the 1970s, when solid-state bargraph displays became the norm.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The design became standardised as DIN 45406.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It evolved into the Type I meter in IEC 60268-10, and it is still known colloquially as a DIN PPM.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Compared to the Type II designs, it has faster integration and return times, a much wider dynamic range and a semi-logarithmic scale, and is calibrated in dB relative to Permitted Maximum Level.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It remains in use in much of northern Europe.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In German broadcasting, the nominal analogue signal corresponding to Permitted Maximum Level was standardised by ARD at 1.55 volts (+6 dBu), and this is the usual sensitivity of a DIN-type PPM for an indication of 0 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Alignment Level (−3 dBu) is shown on the meter by a scale mark at −9.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In Scandinavia a variant of the DIN PPM known as *Nordic* is used.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It has the same integration and return times but a different scale, with *TEST* corresponding to Alignment Level (0 dBu) and +9 corresponding to Permitted Maximum Level (+9 dBu).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Compared to the DIN scale, the Nordic scale is more logarithmic and covers a somewhat smaller dynamic range.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The BBC used a number of methods of measuring programme volume in its early years, including the *volume indicator* and *slide-back voltmeter*.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] By 1932, when the BBC moved to purpose-built facilities in Broadcasting House, the first audio meter called a *programme meter* was introduced.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It was developed by Charles Holt-Smith of the Research Department and became known as the *Smith meter*.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This was the first meter with white markings on a black background.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It was driven by a circuit that gave a roughly logarithmic transfer characteristic, so it could be calibrated in decibels.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The overall characteristics were the product of the driver circuit and the movement's ballistics.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The first of the PPMs was designed by C.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Mayo, also of the BBC's Research Department.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It kept the Smith meter's logarithmic, white-on-black display, and included all the key design features that are still used to this day with only slight modification: full-wave rectification, fast integration and slow return times, and a simple scale calibrated from 1 to 7.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Mayo and others determined the integration and return times by a series of experiments.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] At first, they intended to create a true peak meter to prevent transmitters from exceeding 100% modulation.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] They created a prototype meter with an integration time of about 1 ms.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] They found that the ear tolerates distortion of only a few ms, and that a *registration time* of 4 ms is sufficient.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] They made the return time a compromise between a rapid return, which was tiring to the eye, and a slow return, which made control difficult.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Engineers decided that the meter should take between 2 and 3 seconds to drop back 26 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The BBC PPM became the subject of several formal standards: BS 4297:1968 (superseded); BS5428:Part 9:1981 (superseded) and then BS 6840-10:1991.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The text of the latter is identical to the Type IIa PPM in IEC 60268-10:1991.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Alignment level (0 dBu) and Permitted Maximum Level (+8 dBu) correspond to scale marks 4 and 6 respectively.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The BBC PPM was adopted by commercial broadcasters in the UK.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Other organisations around the world, including the EBU, CBC and ABC used the same dynamics but with slightly different scales.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Modern British PPMs have a 4 dB spacing between the scale marks.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Older designs had a 6 dB spacing between 1 and 2.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This discrepancy can sometimes also be found at the equivalent position on the derived CBC and ABC scales.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] From its inception in 1939 until 2009, the PPM display was available in the form of an electromechanical, moving-coil meter movement with a demanding ballistic specification.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] For many years these were manufactured by Ernest Turner and Company, and in later years by Sifam, based in Torquay.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In 2009, Sifam announced it was ending production of the Type 74 dual-needle meter movement.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In 2010, Sifam ended all PPM meter movement manufacturing.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Three major users—Bryant Unlimited, Canford Audio, and TSL—placed final orders with Sifam for large stocks of the meters to supply manufacturing and maintenance activities for several years.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In the UK, twin-needle PPMs are sometimes used for stereo.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Red and green needles are used for left and right.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] White and yellow needles are used for sum and difference (M and S).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A more recent variation is to use a black needle with a dayglo orange tip for S instead of yellow.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The sensitivity of the S indication can be increased on some meter installations by 20 dB; this is to aid line-up procedures, e.g., of stereo mic pairs, or the azimuth of analogue tape machine heads, which rely on cancellation of the S signal.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] M and S meters are normally aligned to the M6 standard in which M = (L + R) − 6 dB and S = (L − R) − 6 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In other words, the sum and difference signals are each attenuated by 6 dB before being displayed on the meter.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] As a result, signals of identical amplitude and phase in the left and right channels make the M meter show exactly the same deflection as for the individual L and R meters.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This is because summing two identical signals produces a result 6 dB louder than either source, but the M and S meters show summed signals attenuated by 6 dB to compensate.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The M6 standard means that dual mono sources (e.g. a presenter panned to the centre of a stereo sound stage) can be peaked to 6 in both channels, with the M meter also showing 6.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The M6 format has largely replaced the earlier M3 standard in which the sum and difference attenuation is only 3 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This M3 format is designed to give a more accurate indication of the level of the summed mono signal when working with conventional stereo material.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The premise is that in summing two signals of similar level but carrying non-phase-coherent sounds (i.e., typical stereo material), the result averages 3 dB more than either source channel (rather than 6 dB more).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The M3 standard means that true stereo material can be peaked to 6 in both channels, with the M meter also showing 6.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] However, dual-mono sources can only be peaked to 5.25 in each channel to keep the M meter at 6.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Note: the chosen M6/M3 metering standard does not affect the relative audible balance of sounds panned to one side versus the centre – that is determined solely by the panning law of the mixing console's pan-pot.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The M6 standard is deemed a simpler form of metering for untrained broadcasters to use as it keeps the M meter at 4 for Alignment Level and 6 for peaks, without the operator having to remember to subtract 3 dB.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Commercial broadcasting in the UK initially used M3 but had switched to M6 by 1980.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This was mandated by the IBA's Engineering Code of Practice.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The BBC now uses M6 in both radio and TV, although much legacy equipment is still configured for the *traditional* M3 standard.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The EBU PPM is a variant of the British PPM designed for the control of programme levels in international programme exchange.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It is formalised as the Type IIb PPM in IEC 60268-10.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It is identical to the British PPM except for the scale plate, which is calibrated in dB relative to Alignment Level, which is marked *TEST*.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] There are also ticks at 2 dB intervals and at +9 dB, corresponding to Permitted Maximum Level.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In the late 1930s PPMs were considered for use in the US, but rejected in favour of a *Standard Volume Indicator* (VU meter) on grounds of cost.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Joint research by CBS, NBC and Bell Labs found that using an experimental design of PPM (with a relatively long integration time of 25 ms) in the control of programme levels gave only a 1 dB advantage over the VU meter, in terms of average output level for a given amount of distortion.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It was felt that this was too small to justify the much greater expense.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It was also found that VU meters gave more consistent readings than PPMs when comparing programme levels at the sending and receiving end of long lines subject to group delay, which altered the waveform.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This finding has been disputed by others.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A widely believed myth is that the PPM was developed as a superior alternative to the VU meter.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In fact, the PPM came first, and if anything, the VU meter was developed as an economical alternative to the PPM.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] By 1980, ABC had about 100 PPMs in use in control rooms in New York and its Washington News Bureau, and was ordering new consoles with PPMs fitted.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] These were Type II PPMs with the seven marks labelled −22, −16, −12, −8, −4, 0 and +4.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] ABC found that a modified version of the EBU meter based on the VU-meter *A scale* was best, since it let operators use their usual jargon such as *zero level* etc.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The appearance is similar to an EBU scale except that the numbers are 8 dB lower.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] To aid alignment on both VU meters and PPMS, ABC in New York used a special test signal known as ATS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A 440 Hz tone alternated between a steady tone at +8 dBu (indicated at 0 VU and −8 PPM) and tone bursts at +16 dBu (indicated at 0 VU and 0 PPM).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] By 1978 PPMs were in use at the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation's Vancouver plant.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Some 30 or 40 PPMs were in use, with just one or two VU meters retained for settling telco disputes.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] These are Type II PPMs with the seven marks labelled −6, 0, +4, +8, +12, +16 and +20: this scaling shows absolute levels in dBu (or dBm into 600 Ω).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The appearance is similar to the ABC PPM except that all the numbers are 16 dB higher.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) uses a Type II PPM modified with a black-on-white scale plate calibrated in percentage and dB relative to Permitted Maximum Level, which is +6 dBu.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] IEC 60268-18 is a partial standard for a PPM designed for use with digital audio in both professional and consumer use, using "incremental dot or bar type displays or numerical displays".
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Such a display shows level relative to 0 dBFS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The integration time can have any value less than 5 ms − thus, both true-peak and quasi-peak meters can comply, and different meters may indicate very different levels despite compliance with the standard.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The return time has the same value as a Type I meter: 1.7±0.3 seconds for a 20 dB fall.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] IEC 60268-10 specifies three variants: Types I, IIa and IIb, known colloquially as the DIN, British and EBU types respectively.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Types IIa and IIb differ only in the scale marks.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The Nordic, ABC, CBC and SABC variants are not specified in IEC 60268-10.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The Nordic PPM uses Type I ballistics with a different scale.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The ABC, CBC and SABC variants use Type II ballistics with different scales.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Parameters for the VU meter and Nagra modulometer are included in the table below for comparison.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Some information has been obtained from ITU-T Rec.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The *modulometer* is a proprietary type of quasi-PPM found on Nagra products.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It has an integration time (−2 dB) of 7.5 ms, and a semi-logarithmic scale with an appearance between that of a VU meter and a DIN-type PPM.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] A stereo version ("double modulometer") uses a meter movement with two coaxial needles.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In typical practice for Nagra analogue tape recorders, Alignment Level is regarded as −8 and maximum level 0.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Thus, sound recordists using location mixers would typically send a tone at 0 VU or PPM 4 (British) and adjust the Nagra recorder's gain to read −8 on the modulometer.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Some newer digital recorders, e.g., the Nagra VI, have modulometers displayed as bargraphs calibrated in dBFS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] For these, Alignment Level is as for any other digital PPM, i.e., −18 dBFS (EBU) or −20 dBFS (SMPTE).
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] To use PPMs effectively to control sound levels, it is necessary to understand the design rationale and limitations.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Many engineers prefer the PPM to the much slower VU meter used in the US, but it does require some interpretation in use.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Though it gives a useful overload warning, it does not represent either true peak level or subjective loudness.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The BBC has tables showing recommended settings for different types of programme, such as speech, classical music, etc., which attempt to take account of the latter.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Regardless of the kind of programme, there is usually a nominal Permitted Maximum Level, as indicated on a PPM.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Operators are expected to keep levels below it, within reason.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Practices vary between countries and organisations.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] In the UK, the Permitted Maximum Level is 8 dB above Alignment Level, corresponding to 6 on the British PPM scale.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] ITU-T standards for international sound programme circuits specify a Permitted Maximum Level of 9 dB above Alignment Level.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Accordingly, +9 dB is represented by a mark on the EBU PPM scale.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Because quasi-peak PPMs indicate neither loudness nor true peaks but something between the two, it is important to allow sufficient headroom when using them in the control of digital audio levels.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The EBU convention (R68) provides for this by defining Alignment Level as −18 dBFS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] Thus a peak to the Permitted Maximum Level *as indicated on a quasi-PPM* corresponds to −9 or −10 dBFS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] This 9-10 dB margin allows for operator error, the true peak typically being several dB higher than the PPM indication, and that subsequent signal processing (e.g., sample rate conversion) may increase the amplitude.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] SMPTE RP 0155 recommends a different alignment level, corresponding to 0 VU, of −20 dBFS.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The two conventions result in line-up tone levels that differ by 2 dB, but in practice the level of programme modulation tends to be similar.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] IEC 60268-10 is concerned mainly with the highly specified Type I and Type II PPMs used in broadcasting.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] It does, however, also contain a brief section on PPMs for *secondary and consumer* applications.
[src:audio-limiter/peak-programme-meter] The requirements include a minimum of a 12-segment bargraph type display covering a range of −42 dB to +6 dB relative to nominal maximum level, and the same integration and return times as a Type I PPM.
